# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The **Arts and Crafts movement** was an international trend in the decorative and fine arts that developed earliest and most fully in the British Isles and subsequently spread across the British Empire and to the rest of Europe and North America.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Broadly, the beginning of the movement can be dated to the 1880s, with the term itself first used in 1887, and by about 1920 it can be considered as over in the UK, although the term continued in spurious use for various popular elements in design.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Initiated in reaction against the perceived impoverishment of the decorative arts and the conditions in which they were produced, the movement flourished in Europe and North America between about 1880 and 1920.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some consider that it is the root of the Modern Style, a British expression of what later came to be called the Art Nouveau movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Others regard it as the incarnation of Art Nouveau in England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Others consider Art and Crafts to be in opposition to Art Nouveau.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Arts and Crafts indeed criticised Art Nouveau for its use of industrial materials such as iron.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Japan, it emerged in the 1920s as the Mingei movement, promoting traditional craftsmanship.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Cobden-Sanderson at a meeting of the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society in 1887, although the principles and style on which it was based had been developing in England for at least 20 years.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was inspired by the ideas of historian Thomas Carlyle, art critic John Ruskin, and designer William Morris.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Scotland, it is associated with key figures such as Charles Rennie Mackintosh.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Viollet-le-Duc's books on nature and Gothic art also play an essential part in the aesthetics of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts movement emerged from the attempt to reform design and decoration in mid-19th-century Britain.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was a reaction against a perceived decline in standards that the reformers associated with machinery and factory production.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Their critique was sharpened by the items that they saw in Great Exhibition of 1851, which they considered to be excessively ornate, artificial, and ignorant of the qualities of the materials used.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Art historian Nikolaus Pevsner writes that the exhibits showed "ignorance of that basic need in creating patterns, the integrity of the surface", as well as displaying "vulgarity in detail".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Design reform began with Exhibition organisers Henry Cole (1808–1882), Owen Jones (1809–1874), Matthew Digby Wyatt (1820–1877), and Richard Redgrave (1804–1888), all of whom deprecated excessive ornament and impractical or badly-made things.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The *Grammar of Ornament* was particularly influential, liberally distributed as a student prize and running into nine reprints by 1910.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Jones declared that ornament "must be secondary to the thing decorated", that there must be "fitness in the ornament to the thing ornamented", and that wallpapers and carpets must not have any patterns "suggestive of anything but a level or plain".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A fabric or wallpaper in the Great Exhibition might be decorated with a natural motif made to look as real as possible, whereas these writers advocated flat and simplified natural motifs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Redgrave insisted that "style" demanded sound construction before ornamentation, and a proper awareness of the quality of materials used.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] However, the design reformers of the mid-19th century did not go as far as the designers of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] They were more concerned with ornamentation than construction, they had an incomplete understanding of methods of manufacture, and they did not criticise industrial methods as such.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By contrast, the Arts and Crafts movement was as much a movement of social reform as design reform, and its leading practitioners did not separate the two.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some of the ideas of the movement were anticipated by Augustus Pugin (1812–1852), a leader in the Gothic Revival in architecture.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] For example, he advocated truth to material, structure, and function, as did the Arts and Crafts artists.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Pugin articulated the tendency of social critics to compare the faults of modern society with the Middle Ages, such as the sprawling growth of cities and the treatment of the poor – a tendency that became routine with Ruskin, Morris, and the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts philosophy was derived in large measure from John Ruskin's social criticism, deeply influenced by the work of Thomas Carlyle.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ruskin related the moral and social health of a nation to the qualities of its architecture and to the nature of its work.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ruskin considered the sort of mechanised production and division of labour that had been created in the Industrial Revolution to be "servile labour", and he thought that a healthy and moral society required independent workers who designed the things that they made.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He believed factory-made works to be "dishonest," and that handwork and craftsmanship merged dignity with labour.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] On the artistic side Ruskin was influenced by his contemporary Viollet-le-Duc whom he taught to all of his pupils.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In a letter to one of his pupils Ruskin writes: "There is only one book of architecture of any value and that contains every thing, rightly, Monsieur Viollet-le-Duc's Dictionary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] According to some, Ruskin's influence on Arts and Crafts was supplanted in 1860 by that of Viollet-le-Duc.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His followers favoured craft production over industrial manufacture and were concerned about the loss of traditional skills, but they were more troubled by the effects of the factory system than by machinery itself.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris's idea of "handicraft" was essentially work without any division of labour rather than work without any sort of machinery.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris admired Ruskin's *The Seven Lamps of Architecture* and *The Stones of Venice* and had read *Modern Painters*, but he did not share Ruskin's admiration for J.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Turner and his writings on art indicate a lack of interest in easel painting as such.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] On his side, Ruskin dissented firmly from the idea that became Arts-and-Crafts orthodoxy, that decoration should be flat and should not represent three-dimensional forms.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris (1834–1896) was the towering figure in late 19th-century design and the main influence on the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The aesthetic and social vision of the movement grew out of ideas that he developed in the 1850s with the Birmingham Set – a group of students at the University of Oxford including Edward Burne-Jones, who combined a love of Romantic literature with a commitment to social reform.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] John William Mackail notes that, for the Set, "Carlyle's *Past and Present* stood alongside of [Ruskin's] *Modern Painters* as inspired and absolute truth." The medievalism of Malory's *Morte d'Arthur* set the standard for their early style.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Burne-Jones' words, they intended to "wage Holy warfare against the age".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris began experimenting with various crafts and designing furniture and interiors.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He was personally involved in manufacture as well as design, which was the hallmark of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ruskin had argued that the separation of the intellectual act of design from the manual act of physical creation was both socially and aesthetically damaging.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris further developed this idea, insisting that no work should be carried out in his workshops before he had personally mastered the appropriate techniques and materials, arguing that "without dignified, creative human occupation people became disconnected from life".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1861, Morris began making furniture and decorative objects commercially, modelling his designs on medieval styles and using bold forms and strong colours.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His patterns were based on flora and fauna, and his products were inspired by the vernacular or domestic traditions of the British countryside.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some were deliberately left unfinished in order to display the beauty of the materials and the work of the craftsman, thus creating a rustic appearance.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris strove to unite all the arts within the decoration of the home, emphasising nature and simplicity of form.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris shared Ruskin's critique of industrial society and at one time or another attacked the modern factory, the use of machinery, the division of labour, capitalism and the loss of traditional craft methods.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] But his attitude to machinery was inconsistent.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He said at one point that production by machinery was "altogether an evil", but at others times, he was willing to commission work from manufacturers who were able to meet his standards with the aid of machines.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris said that in a "true society", where neither luxuries nor cheap trash were made, machinery could be improved and used to reduce the hours of labour.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris insisted that the artist should be a craftsman-designer working by hand and advocated a society of free craftspeople, such as he believed had existed during the Middle Ages.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] "Because craftsmen took pleasure in their work", he wrote, "the Middle Ages was a period of greatness in the art of the common people. ...
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris's followers also had differing views about machinery and the factory system.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee, a central figure in the Arts and Crafts movement, said in 1888, that, "We do not reject the machine, we welcome it.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris and his followers believed the division of labour on which modern industry depended was undesirable, but the extent to which every design should be carried out by the designer was a matter for debate and disagreement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Not all Arts and Crafts artists carried out every stage in the making of goods themselves, and it was only in the 20th century that that became essential to the definition of craftsmanship.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Although Morris was famous for getting hands-on experience himself of many crafts (including weaving, dyeing, printing, calligraphy and embroidery), he did not regard the separation of designer and executant in his factory as problematic.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Walter Crane, a close political associate of Morris's, took an unsympathetic view of the division of labour on both moral and artistic grounds, and strongly advocated that designing and making should come from the same hand.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Lewis Foreman Day, a friend and contemporary of Crane's, as unstinting as Crane in his admiration of Morris, disagreed strongly with Crane.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He thought that the separation of design and execution was not only inevitable in the modern world, but also that only that sort of specialisation allowed the best in design and the best in making.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Few of the founders of the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society insisted that the designer should also be the maker, although they considered it important that the maker should be credited, which was the practice in the catalogues of their exhibitions.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Many of the Arts and Crafts movement designers were socialists, including Morris, T.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee, Philip Webb, Charles Faulkner, and A.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In the early 1880s, Morris was spending more of his time on promoting socialism than on designing and making.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee established a community of craftsmen called the Guild of Handicraft in east London, later moving to Chipping Campden.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Those adherents who were not socialists, such as Alfred Hoare Powell, advocated a more humane and personal relationship between employer and employee.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Lewis Foreman Day was another successful and influential Arts and Crafts designer who was not a socialist, despite his long friendship with Crane.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Britain, the movement was associated with dress reform, ruralism, the garden city movement and the folk-song revival.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] All were linked, in some degree, by the ideal of "the Simple Life".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In continental Europe the movement was associated with the preservation of national traditions in building, the applied arts, domestic design and costume.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris's designs quickly became popular, attracting interest when his company's work was exhibited at the 1862 International Exhibition in London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Much of this work is directly inspired from the Dictionnaire of Viollet-le-Duc.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Most of Morris & Co's early work was for churches and Morris won important interior design commissions at St James's Palace and the South Kensington Museum (now the Victoria and Albert Museum).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Later his work became popular with the middle and upper classes, despite his wish to create a democratic art, and by the end of the 19th century, Arts and Crafts design in houses and domestic interiors was the dominant style in Britain, copied in products made by conventional industrial methods.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The spread of Arts and Crafts ideas during the late 19th and early 20th centuries resulted in the establishment of many associations and craft communities, although Morris had little to do with them because of his preoccupation with socialism at the time.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A hundred and thirty Arts and Crafts organisations were formed in Britain, most between 1895 and 1905.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Mackmurdo formed the Century Guild, a partnership of designers including Selwyn Image, Herbert Horne, Clement Heaton and Benjamin Creswick.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1884, the Art Workers Guild was initiated by five young architects, William Lethaby, Edward Prior, Ernest Newton, Mervyn Macartney and Gerald C.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Horsley, with the goal of bringing together fine and applied arts and raising the status of the latter.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was directed originally by George Blackall Simonds.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By 1890 the Guild had 150 members, representing the increasing number of practitioners of the Arts and Crafts style.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The London department store Liberty, founded in 1875, was a prominent retailer of goods in the style and of the "artistic dress" favoured by followers of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1887, the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society, which gave its name to the movement, was formed with Walter Crane as president, holding its first exhibition in the New Gallery, London, in November 1888.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It was the first show of contemporary decorative arts in London since the Grosvenor Gallery's Winter Exhibition of 1881.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris & Co. was well represented in the exhibition with furniture, fabrics, carpets and embroideries.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Edward Burne-Jones observed, "here for the first time one can measure a bit the change that has happened in the last twenty years".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The society still exists as the Society of Designer Craftsmen.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee, a major late practitioner of the style in England, founded the Guild and School of Handicraft in the East End of London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The guild was a craft co-operative modelled on the medieval guilds and intended to give working men satisfaction in their craftsmanship.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Skilled craftsmen, working on the principles of Ruskin and Morris, were to produce hand-crafted goods and manage a school for apprentices.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The idea was greeted with enthusiasm by almost everyone except Morris, who was by now involved with promoting socialism and thought Ashbee's scheme trivial.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] From 1888 to 1902 the guild prospered, employing about 50 men.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In 1902 Ashbee relocated the guild out of London to begin an experimental community in Chipping Campden in the Cotswolds.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The guild's work is characterised by plain surfaces of hammered silver, flowing wirework and coloured stones in simple settings.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Ashbee designed jewellery and silver tableware.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The guild flourished at Chipping Camden but did not prosper and was liquidated in 1908.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some craftsmen stayed, contributing to the tradition of modern craftsmanship in the area.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Voysey (1857–1941) was an Arts and Crafts architect who also designed fabrics, tiles, ceramics, furniture and metalwork.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His style combined simplicity with sophistication.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His wallpapers and textiles, featuring stylised bird and plant forms in bold outlines with flat colours, were used widely.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Morris's thought influenced the distributism of G.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By 1910, there was a fashion for "Arts and Crafts" and all things hand-made.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society held eleven exhibitions between 1888 and 1916.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By the outbreak of war in 1914 it was in decline and faced a crisis.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Its 1912 exhibition had been a financial failure.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Nikolaus Pevsner in his book *Pioneers of Modern Design* presents the Arts and Crafts movement as design radicals who influenced the modern movement, but failed to change and were eventually superseded by it.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The British artist potter Bernard Leach brought to England many ideas he had developed in Japan with the social critic Yanagi Soetsu about the moral and social value of simple crafts; both were enthusiastic readers of Ruskin.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Leach was an active propagandist for these ideas, which struck a chord with practitioners of the crafts in the inter-war years, and he expounded them in *A Potter's Book*, published in 1940, which denounced industrial society in terms as vehement as those of Ruskin and Morris.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Thus the Arts and Crafts philosophy was perpetuated among British craft workers in the 1950s and 1960s, long after the demise of the Arts and Crafts movement and at the high tide of Modernism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] British Utility furniture of the 1940s also derived from Arts and Crafts principles.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] One of its main promoters, Gordon Russell, chairman of the Utility Furniture Design Panel, was imbued with Arts and Crafts ideas.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] He manufactured furniture in the Cotswold Hills, a region of Arts and Crafts furniture-making since Ashbee, and he was a member of the Arts and Crafts Exhibition Society.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] William Morris's biographer, Fiona MacCarthy, detected the Arts and Crafts philosophy even behind the Festival of Britain (1951), the work of the designer Terence Conran (1931–2020) and the founding of the British Crafts Council in the 1970s.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The beginnings of the Arts and Crafts movement in Scotland were in the stained glass revival of the 1850s, pioneered by James Ballantine (1806–1877).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His major works included the great west window of Dunfermline Abbey and the scheme for St Giles Cathedral, Edinburgh.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Glasgow it was pioneered by Daniel Cottier (1838–1891), who had probably studied with Ballantine, and was directly influenced by William Morris, Ford Madox Brown and John Ruskin.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His key works included the *Baptism of Christ* in Paisley Abbey, (c.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His followers included Stephen Adam and his son of the same name.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Glasgow-born designer and theorist Christopher Dresser (1834–1904) was one of the first, and most important, independent designers, a pivotal figure in the Aesthetic Movement and a major contributor to the allied Anglo-Japanese movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The movement had an "extraordinary flowering" in Scotland where it was represented by the development of the 'Glasgow Style' which was based on the talent of the Glasgow School of Art.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Celtic revival took hold here, and motifs such as the Glasgow rose became popularised.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Charles Rennie Mackintosh (1868–1928) and the Glasgow School of Art were to influence others worldwide.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The situation in Wales was different from elsewhere in the UK.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Insofar as craftsmanship was concerned, Arts and Crafts was a *revivalist* campaign.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] But in Wales, at least until the First World War, a genuine craft tradition still existed.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Local materials, stone or clay, continued to be used as a matter of course.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Scotland become known in the Arts and Crafts movement for its stained glass; Wales would become known for its pottery.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] By the mid 19th century, the heavy, salt glazes used for generations by local craftsmen had gone out of fashion, not least as mass-produced ceramics undercut prices.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] But the Arts and Crafts Movement brought new appreciation to their work.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Horace W Elliot, an English gallerist, visited the Ewenny Pottery (which dated back to the 17th century) in 1885, to both find local pieces and encourage a style compatible with the movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The pieces he brought back to London for the next twenty years revivified interest in Welsh pottery work.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A key promoter of the Arts and Crafts movement in Wales was Owen Morgan Edwards.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Edwards was a reforming politician dedicated to renewing Welsh pride by exposing its people to their own language and history.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] For Edwards, "There is nothing that Wales requires more than an education in the arts and crafts." – though Edwards was more inclined to resurrecting Welsh Nationalism than admiring glazes or rustic integrity.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In architecture, Clough Williams-Ellis sought to renew interest in ancient building, reviving "rammed earth" or pisé construction in Britain.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The movement spread to Ireland, representing an important time for the nation's cultural development, a visual counterpart to the literary revival of the same time and was a publication of Irish nationalism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Arts and Crafts use of stained glass was popular in Ireland, with Harry Clarke the best-known artist and also with Evie Hone.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The architecture of the style is represented by the Honan Chapel (1916) in Cork city in the grounds of University College Cork.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Other architects practising in Ireland included Sir Edwin Lutyens (Heywood House in Co.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Laois, Lambay Island and the Irish National War Memorial Gardens in Dublin) and Frederick 'Pa' Hicks (Malahide Castle estate buildings and round tower).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Irish Celtic motifs were popular with the movement in silvercraft, carpet design, book illustrations, and hand-carved furniture.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Widely exhibited in Europe, the Arts and Crafts style's simplicity inspired designers like Henry van de Velde and styles such as Art Nouveau, the Dutch De Stijl group, Vienna Secession, and eventually the Bauhaus style.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Pevsner regarded the style as a prelude to Modernism, which used simple forms without ornamentation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The earliest Arts and Crafts activity in continental Europe was in Belgium in about 1890, where the English style inspired artists and architects including Henry Van de Velde, Gabriel Van Dievoet, Gustave Serrurier-Bovy, and a group known as *La Libre Esthétique* (Free Aesthetic).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Arts and Crafts products were admired in Austria and Germany in the early 20th century, and under their inspiration design moved rapidly forward while it stagnated in Britain.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Wiener Werkstätte, founded in 1903 by Josef Hoffmann and Koloman Moser, was influenced by the Arts and Crafts principles of the "unity of the arts" and the hand-made.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] However, its leading members, van de Velde and Hermann Muthesius, had conflicting opinions about standardisation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Muthesius believed that it was essential were Germany to become a leading nation in trade and culture.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Finland, an idealistic artists' colony in Helsinki was designed by Herman Gesellius, Armas Lindgren, and Eliel Saarinen, who worked in the National Romantic style, akin to the British Gothic Revival.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Hungary, under the influence of Ruskin and Morris, a group of artists and architects, including Károly Kós, Aladár Körösfői-Kriesch, and Ede Toroczkai Wigand, discovered the folk art and vernacular architecture of Transylvania.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Many of Kós's buildings, including those in the Budapest zoo and the Wekerle estate in the same city, show this influence.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Russia, Viktor Hartmann, Viktor Vasnetsov, Yelena Polenova, and other artists associated with Abramtsevo Colony sought to revive the quality of medieval Russian decorative arts quite independently from the movement in Great Britain.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Iceland, Sölvi Helgason's work shows Arts and Crafts influence.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In the United States, the Arts and Crafts style initiated a variety of attempts to reinterpret European Arts and Crafts ideals for Americans.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] These included the "Craftsman"-style architecture, furniture, and other decorative arts such as designs promoted by Gustav Stickley in his magazine, *The Craftsman* and designs produced on the Roycroft campus as publicised in Elbert Hubbard's *The Fra*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Both men used their magazines as a vehicle to promote the goods produced with the Craftsman workshop in Eastwood, New York, and Elbert Hubbard's Roycroft campus in East Aurora, New York.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] A host of imitators of Stickley's furniture (the designs of which are often mislabelled the "Mission Style") included three companies established by his brothers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The terms *American Craftsman* or ***Craftsman style*** are often used to denote the style of architecture, interior design, and decorative arts that prevailed between the dominant eras of Art Nouveau and Art Deco in the US, or approximately the period from 1910 to 1925.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The movement was particularly notable for the professional opportunities it opened up for women as artisans, designers and entrepreneurs who founded and ran, or were employed by, such successful enterprises as the Kalo Shops, Pewabic Pottery, Rookwood Pottery, and Tiffany Studios.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Canada, the term *Arts and Crafts* predominates, but *Craftsman* is also recognised.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] While the Europeans tried to recreate the virtuous crafts being replaced by industrialisation, Americans tried to establish a new type of virtue to replace heroic craft production: well-decorated middle-class homes.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] They claimed that the simple but refined aesthetics of Arts and Crafts decorative arts would ennoble the new experience of industrial consumerism, making individuals more rational and society more harmonious.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The American Arts and Crafts movement was the aesthetic counterpart of its contemporary political philosophy, progressivism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Characteristically, when the Arts and Crafts Society began in October 1897 in Chicago, it was at Hull House, one of the first American settlement houses for social reform.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Arts and Crafts ideals disseminated in America through journal and newspaper writing were supplemented by societies that sponsored lectures.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first was organised in Boston in the late 1890s, when a group of influential architects, designers, and educators determined to bring to America the design reforms begun in Britain by William Morris; they met to organise an exhibition of contemporary craft objects.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first meeting was held on 4 January 1897, at the Museum of Fine Arts (MFA) in Boston to organise an exhibition of contemporary crafts.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] When craftsmen, consumers, and manufacturers realised the aesthetic and technical potential of the applied arts, the process of design reform in Boston started.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Present at this meeting were General Charles Loring, Chairman of the Trustees of the MFA; William Sturgis Bigelow and Denman Ross, collectors, writers and MFA trustees; Ross Turner, painter; Sylvester Baxter, art critic for the *Boston Transcript*; Howard Baker, A.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Longfellow Jr.; and Ralph Clipson Sturgis, architect.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first American Arts and Crafts Exhibition began on 5 April 1897, at Copley Hall, Boston, featuring more than 1000 objects made by 160 craftsmen, half of whom were women.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Some of the advocates of the exhibit were Langford Warren, founder of Harvard's School of Architecture; Mrs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Richard Morris Hunt; Arthur Astor Carey and Edwin Mead, social reformers; and Will H.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Castle in the Clouds (also known as *Lucknow*), a mountaintop estate in the Ossipee Mountains of New Hampshire, built in 1913–14 by the Boston architect J.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Hapgood, and the contemporary studio craft style.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Batchelder in Pasadena, California, and idiosyncratic furniture of Charles Rohlfs all demonstrate the influence of Arts and Crafts.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Canada, artist, teacher and architect George Agnew Reid (1860–1947) was a major proponent of the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Reid was interested in linking art and social issues, and he felt strongly that visual and applied arts could act as tools for personal and social improvement through public access to beauty and good design.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Reid brought his "art for life's sake" sensibility to his painting practice, specifically with the murals he created in and around Toronto.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Restored and landmark-protected examples are still present in America, especially in California in Berkeley and Pasadena, and the sections of other towns originally developed during the era and not experiencing post-war urban renewal.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Mission Revival, Prairie School, and the 'California bungalow' styles of residential building remain popular in the United States today.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] As theoreticians, educators, and prolific artists in mediums from printmaking to pottery and pastel, two of the most influential figures were Arthur Wesley Dow (1857–1922) on the East Coast and Pedro Joseph de Lemos (1882–1954) in California.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] His purpose was to create objects that were finely crafted and beautifully rendered.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Among his unorthodox teachings was his belief that manufactured products could express "the sublime beauty" and that great insight was to be found in the abstract "design forms" of pre-Columbian civilisations.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The Museum of the American Arts and Crafts Movement (MAACM) in St Petersburg, Florida, displays an extensive collection of fine and decorative arts from the American Arts and Crafts movement (c.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] In Japan, Yanagi Sōetsu, creator of the Mingei movement which promoted folk art from the 1920s onwards, was influenced by the writings of Morris and Ruskin.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Like the Arts and Crafts movement in Europe, Mingei sought to preserve traditional crafts and often used medieval, romantic, or folk styles of decoration.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It advocated economic and social reform and was anti-industrial in its orientation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] It had a strong influence on the arts in Europe until it was displaced by Modernism in the 1930s, and its influence continued among craft makers, designers, and town planners long afterwards.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Many of the leaders of the Arts and Crafts movement were trained as architects (e.g.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Lethaby) and it was on building that the movement had its most visible and lasting influence.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Red House, in Bexleyheath, London, designed for Morris in 1859 by architect Philip Webb, exemplifies the early Arts and Crafts style, with its well-proportioned solid forms, wide porches, steep roof, pointed window arches, brick fireplaces and wooden fittings.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Webb rejected classical and other revivals of historical styles based on grand buildings, and based his design on British vernacular architecture, expressing the texture of ordinary materials, such as stone and tiles, with an asymmetrical and picturesque building composition.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The London suburb of Bedford Park, built mainly in the 1880s and 1890s, has about 360 Arts and Crafts style houses and was once famous for its Aesthetic residents.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Several Almshouses were built in the Arts and Crafts style, for example, Whiteley Village, Surrey, built between 1914 and 1917, with over 280 buildings, and the Dyers Almshouses, Sussex, built between 1939 and 1971.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Letchworth Garden City, the first garden city, was inspired by Arts and Crafts ideals.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The first houses were designed by Barry Parker and Raymond Unwin in the vernacular style popularised by the movement and the town became associated with high-mindedness and simple living.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Gertrude Jekyll applied Arts and Crafts principles to garden design.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] She worked with the English architect, Sir Edwin Lutyens, for whose projects she created numerous landscapes, and who designed her home Munstead Wood, near Godalming in Surrey.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Jekyll created the gardens for Bishopsbarns, the home of York architect Walter Brierley, an exponent of the Arts and Crafts movement and known as the "Lutyens of the North".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] The garden for Brierley's final project, Goddards in York, was the work of George Dillistone, a gardener who worked with Lutyens and Jekyll at Castle Drogo.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] At Goddards the garden incorporated a number of features that reflected the arts and crafts style of the house, such as the use of hedges and herbaceous borders to divide the garden into a series of outdoor rooms.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Another notable Arts and Crafts garden is Hidcote Manor Garden designed by Lawrence Johnston which is also laid out in a series of outdoor rooms and where, like Goddards, the landscaping becomes less formal further away from the house.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p01] Other examples of Arts and Crafts gardens include Hestercombe Gardens, Lytes Cary Manor and the gardens of some of the architectural examples of arts and crafts buildings (listed above).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Morris's ideas were adopted by the New Education Movement in the late 1880s, which incorporated handicraft teaching in schools at Abbotsholme (1889) and Bedales (1892), and his influence has been noted in the social experiments of Dartington Hall during the mid-20th century.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Arts and Crafts practitioners in Britain were critical of the government system of art education based on design in the abstract with little teaching of practical craft.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] This lack of craft training also caused concern in industrial and official circles, and in 1884 a Royal Commission (accepting the advice of William Morris) recommended that art education should pay more attention to the suitability of design to the material in which it was to be executed.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] The first school to make this change was the Birmingham School of Arts and Crafts, which "led the way in introducing executed design to the teaching of art and design nationally (working in the material for which the design was intended rather than designing on paper).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Other local authority schools also began to introduce more practical teaching of crafts, and by the 1890s Arts and Crafts ideals were being disseminated by members of the Art Workers Guild into art schools throughout the country.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Members of the Guild held influential positions: Walter Crane was director of the Manchester School of Art and subsequently the Royal College of Art; F.M.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Simpson, Robert Anning Bell and C.J.Allen were respectively professor of architecture, instructor in painting and design, and instructor in sculpture at Liverpool School of Art; Robert Catterson-Smith, the headmaster of the Birmingham Art School from 1902 to 1920, was also an AWG member; W.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Lethaby and George Frampton were inspectors and advisors to the London County Council's (LCC) education board and in 1896, largely as a result of their work, the LCC set up the Central School of Arts and Crafts and made them joint principals.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Until the formation of the Bauhaus in Germany, the Central School was regarded as the most progressive art school in Europe.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Shortly after its foundation, the Camberwell School of Arts and Crafts was set up on Arts and Crafts lines by the local borough council.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] As head of the Royal College of Art in 1898, Crane tried to reform it along more practical lines, but resigned after a year, defeated by the bureaucracy of the Board of Education, who then appointed Augustus Spencer to implement his plan.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Spencer brought in Lethaby to head its school of design and several members of the Art Workers' Guild as teachers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Ten years after reform, a committee of inquiry reviewed the RCA and found that it was still not adequately training students for industry.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] In the debate that followed the publication of the committee's report, C.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Ashbee published a highly critical essay, *Should We Stop Teaching Art*, in which he called for the system of art education to be completely dismantled and for the crafts to be learned in state-subsidised workshops instead.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Lewis Foreman Day, an important figure in the Arts and Crafts movement, took a different view in his dissenting report to the committee of inquiry, arguing for greater emphasis on principles of design against the growing orthodoxy of teaching design by direct working in materials.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/arts-and-crafts-movement-p02] Nevertheless, the Arts and Crafts ethos thoroughly pervaded British art schools and persisted, in the view of the historian of art education, Stuart MacDonald, until after the Second World War.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The **Astley Ainslie Hospital** is a community hospital in The Grange area of Edinburgh, Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] David Ainslie, who died in 1900, left £800,000 for the purpose of building and endowing a hospital or institution for convalescents from the Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] He wanted it to be called the Astley Ainslie Institution.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The hospital opened with 34 beds in 1923.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The landscaping of the grounds was executed by Roland Edgar Cooper, just prior to his becoming Head Curator of the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The site may have had a medical connection since the 1500s.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] Pavilions were added to the east and west in 1929 and a nurses' home was completed in 1930.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] In the 1950s, Colonel John Fraser, while medical superintendent at the hospital, built a collection of ecclesiastical stones, some bearing initials and dates, into a specially constructed stone panel in the south boundary wall of his residence, South Bank.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The Charles Bell children's pavilion was completed in 1965 and the Cunningham Unit (a day centre and outpatient clinic) was completed in 1971.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] A disabled living centre followed in 1979 and the Balfour Pavilion for older people was completed in 1983.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] In 2007 the hospital became the home of the Southeast Mobility and Rehabilitation Technology Centre ("SMART Centre"): the centre was designed to house clinical, technical, office and storage facilities for a range of rehabilitation services.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The centre provides 4,000 m2 of space and cost £7.5 million to construct, incorporating a number of environmentally friendly features.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] In 2014, the health board considered proposals to demolish the hospital and three others, with a view to replacing these facilities with care villages which would consist of buildings more suited to social care.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] By 2021, the 17-hectare (42-acre) campus site was proposed for sale in the late 2020s, provided funding could be obtained for replacement facilities at the Royal Edinburgh Hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The value of the wooded parkland, that is open to the public, was recognised by the local NHS Lothian health board.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The Astley Ainslie Community Trust was set up to campaign to protect the trees in the site.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] Members of the trust include Ian Rankin.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The two thousand trees include some that are unusual in the UK such as Atlas cedar, wellingtonia, cedar of Lebanon, deodar cedar, Bhutan pine and Monterey cypress as well as many more common species of oaks, firs, cherry and chestnuts.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] Some are protected with tree preservation orders.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/astley-ainslie-hospital] The hospital specialises in rehabilitative care for people who have suffered brain injuries, stroke, orthopaedic or cardiac conditions and respite care for elderly people.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 2019, it was reported in an Ofcom report that the BBC spent £136m on news during the period April 2018 to March 2019.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News' domestic, global and online news divisions are housed within the largest live newsroom in Europe, in Broadcasting House in central London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Parliamentary coverage is produced and broadcast from studios in London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Through BBC English Regions, the BBC also has regional centres across England and national news centres in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] All nations and English regions produce their own local news programmes and other current affairs and sport programmes.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC is a quasi-autonomous corporation authorised by royal charter, making it operationally independent of the government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] As of 2024, the BBC reaches an average of 450 million people per week, with the BBC World Service accounting for 320 million people.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The British Broadcasting Company broadcast its first radio bulletin from radio station 2LO on 14 November 1922.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Wishing to avoid competition, newspaper publishers persuaded the government to ban the BBC from broadcasting news before 7 pm, and to force it to use wire service copy instead of reporting on its own.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC gradually gained the right to edit the copy and, in 1934, created its own news operation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] However, it could not broadcast news before 6 p.m. until World War II.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In addition to news, Gaumont British and Movietone cinema newsreels had been broadcast on the TV service since 1936, with the BBC producing its own equivalent *Television Newsreel* programme from January 1948.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A weekly *Children's Newsreel* was inaugurated on 23 April 1950, to around 350,000 receivers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The network began simulcasting its radio news on television in 1946, with a still picture of Big Ben.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Televised bulletins began on 5 July 1954, broadcast from leased studios within Alexandra Palace in London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The public's interest in television and live events was stimulated by Elizabeth II's coronation in 1953.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] It is estimated that up to 27 million people viewed the programme in the UK, overtaking radio's audience of 12 million for the first time.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Those live pictures were fed from 21 cameras in central London to Alexandra Palace for transmission, and then on to other UK transmitters opened in time for the event.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] That year, there were around two million TV Licences held in the UK, rising to over three million the following year, and four and a half million by 1955.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Television news, although physically separate from its radio counterpart, was still firmly under radio news' control in the 1950s.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Correspondents provided reports for both outlets, and the first televised bulletin, shown on 5 July 1954 on the then BBC television service and presented by Richard Baker, involved his providing narration off-screen while stills were shown.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This was then followed by the customary *Television Newsreel* with a recorded commentary by John Snagge (and on other occasions by Andrew Timothy).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On-screen newsreaders were introduced a year later in 1955 – Kenneth Kendall (the first to appear in vision), Robert Dougall, and Richard Baker—three weeks before ITN's launch on 21 September 1955.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Mainstream television production had started to move out of Alexandra Palace in 1950 to larger premises – mainly at Lime Grove Studios in Shepherd's Bush, west London – taking Current Affairs (then known as Talks Department) with it.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] It was from here that the first *Panorama*, a new documentary programme, was transmitted on 11 November 1953, with Richard Dimbleby becoming anchor in 1955.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 1958, Hugh Carleton Greene became head of News and Current Affairs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 1 January 1960, Greene became Director-General.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Greene made changes that were aimed at making BBC reporting more similar to its competitor ITN, which had been highly rated by study groups held by Greene.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A newsroom was created at Alexandra Palace, television reporters were recruited and given the opportunity to write and voice their own scripts, without having to cover stories for radio too.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 20 June 1960, Nan Winton, the first female BBC network newsreader, appeared in vision.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] 19 September 1960 saw the start of the radio news and current affairs programme *The Ten O'clock News*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC2 started transmission on 20 April 1964 and began broadcasting a new show, *Newsroom*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On Sunday 17 September 1967, *The World This Weekend*, a weekly news and current affairs programme, launched on what was then Home Service, but soon-to-be Radio 4.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Preparations for colour began in the autumn of 1967 and on Thursday 7 March 1968 *Newsroom* on BBC2 moved to an early evening slot, becoming the first UK news programme to be transmitted in colour – from Studio A at Alexandra Palace.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] *News Review* and *Westminster* (the latter a weekly review of Parliamentary happenings) were "colourised" shortly after.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] However, much of the insert material was still in black and white, as initially only a part of the film coverage shot in and around London was on colour reversal film stock, and all regional and many international contributions were still in black and white.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Colour facilities at Alexandra Palace were technically very limited for the next eighteen months, as it had only one RCA colour Quadruplex videotape machine and, eventually two Pye plumbicon colour telecines–although the news colour service started with just one.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] *Town and Around* was never to make the move to Television Centre – instead it became *London This Week* which aired on Mondays and Fridays only, from the new TVC studios.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC moved production out of Alexandra Palace in 1969.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC Television News resumed operations the next day with a lunchtime bulletin on BBC1 – in black and white – from Television Centre, where it remained until March 2013.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This move to a smaller studio with better technical facilities allowed *Newsroom* and *News Review* to replace back projection with colour-separation overlay.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] During the 1960s, satellite communication had become possible; however, it was some years before digital line-store conversion was able to undertake the process seamlessly.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 14 September 1970, the first *Nine O'Clock News* was broadcast on television.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Robert Dougall presented the first week from studio N1 – described by *The Guardian* as "a sort of polystyrene padded cell"—the bulletin having been moved from the earlier time of 20.50 as a response to the ratings achieved by ITN's *News at Ten*, introduced three years earlier on the rival ITV.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Richard Baker and Kenneth Kendall presented subsequent weeks, thus echoing those first television bulletins of the mid-1950s.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Angela Rippon became the first female news presenter of the *Nine O'Clock News* in 1975.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Her work outside the news was controversial at the time, appearing on *The Morecambe and Wise Christmas Show* in 1976 singing and dancing.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The first edition of *John Craven's Newsround*, initially intended only as a short series and later renamed just *Newsround*, came from studio N3 on 4 April 1972.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Afternoon television news bulletins during the mid to late 1970s were broadcast from the BBC newsroom itself, rather than one of the three news studios.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The newsreader would present to camera while sitting on the edge of a desk; behind him staff would be seen working busily at their desks.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This period corresponded with when the *Nine O'Clock News* got its next makeover, and would use a CSO background of the newsroom from that very same camera each weekday evening.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Also in the mid-1970s, the late night news on BBC2 was briefly renamed *Newsnight*, but this was not to last, or be the same programme as we know today – that would be launched in 1980 – and it soon reverted to being just a news summary with the early evening BBC2 news expanded to become *Newsday*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] News on radio was to change in the 1970s, and on Radio 4 in particular, brought about by the arrival of new editor Peter Woon from television news and the implementation of the *Broadcasting in the Seventies* report.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] These included the introduction of correspondents into news bulletins where previously only a newsreader would present, as well as the inclusion of content gathered in the preparation process.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] New programmes were also added to the daily schedule, *PM* and *The World Tonight* as part of the plan for the station to become a "wholly speech network".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] *Newsbeat* launched as the news service on Radio 1 on 10 September 1973.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 23 September 1974, a teletext system which was launched to bring news content on television screens using text only was launched.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Engineers originally began developing such a system to bring news to deaf viewers, but the system was expanded.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The Ceefax service became much more diverse before it ceased on 23 October 2012: it not only had subtitling for all channels, it also gave information such as weather, flight times and film reviews.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] By the end of the decade, the practice of shooting on film for inserts in news broadcasts was declining, with the introduction of ENG technology into the UK.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The equipment would gradually become less cumbersome – the BBC's first attempts had been using a Philips colour camera with backpack base station and separate portable Sony U-matic recorder in the latter half of the decade.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 1980, the Iranian Embassy Siege had been shot electronically by the BBC Television News Outside broadcasting team, and the work of reporter Kate Adie, broadcasting live from Prince's Gate, was nominated for BAFTA actuality coverage, but this time beaten by ITN for the 1980 award.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The first BBC breakfast television programme, *Breakfast Time* also launched during the 1980s, on 17 January 1983 from Lime Grove Studio E and two weeks before its ITV rival TV-am.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Frank Bough, Selina Scott, and Nick Ross helped to wake viewers with a relaxed style of presenting.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* first aired on 3 September 1984, eventually becoming the most watched news programme in the UK (however, since 2006 it has been overtaken by the *BBC News at Ten*).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In October 1984, images of millions of people starving to death in the Ethiopian famine were shown in Michael Buerk's *Six O'Clock News* reports.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC News crew were the first to document the famine, with Buerk's report on 23 October describing it as "a biblical famine in the 20th century" and "the closest thing to hell on Earth".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC News report shocked Britain, motivating its citizens to inundate relief agencies, such as Save the Children, with donations, and to bring global attention to the crisis in Ethiopia.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The news report was also watched by Bob Geldof, who would organise the charity single "Do They Know It's Christmas?" to raise money for famine relief followed by the Live Aid concert in July 1985.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Starting in 1981, the BBC gave a common theme to its main news bulletins with new electronic titles–a set of computer-animated "stripes" forming a circle on a red background with a "BBC News" typescript appearing below the circle graphics, and a theme tune consisting of brass and keyboards.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The *Nine* used a similar (striped) number 9.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The red background was replaced by a blue from 1985 until 1987.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 1987, John Birt resurrected the practice of correspondents working for both TV and radio with the introduction of bi-media journalism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] During the 1990s, a wider range of services began to be offered by BBC News, with the split of BBC World Service Television to become BBC World (news and current affairs), and BBC Prime (light entertainment).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Content for a 24-hour news channel was thus required, followed in 1997 with the launch of domestic equivalent BBC News 24.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Rather than set bulletins, ongoing reports and coverage was needed to keep both channels functioning and meant a greater emphasis in budgeting for both was necessary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 1998, after 66 years at Broadcasting House, the **BBC Radio News** operation moved to BBC Television Centre.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] New technology, provided by Silicon Graphics, came into use in 1993 for a re-launch of the main BBC 1 bulletins, creating a virtual set which appeared to be much larger than it was physically.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The relaunch also brought all bulletins into the same style of set with only small changes in colouring, titles, and music to differentiate each.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A computer generated cut-glass sculpture of the BBC coat of arms was the centrepiece of the programme titles until the large scale corporate rebranding of news services in 1999.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In November 1997, BBC News Online was launched, following individual webpages for major news events such as the 1996 Olympic Games, 1997 general election, and the death of Princess Diana.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 1999, the biggest relaunch occurred, with BBC One bulletins, BBC World, BBC News 24, and BBC News Online all adopting a common style.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] One of the most significant changes was the gradual adoption of the corporate image by the BBC regional news programmes, giving a common style across local, national and international BBC television news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This also included *Newyddion*, the main news programme of Welsh language channel S4C, produced by BBC News Wales.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Following the relaunch of BBC News in 1999, regional headlines were included at the start of the BBC One news bulletins in 2000.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The English regions did however lose five minutes at the end of their bulletins, due to a new headline round-up at 18:55.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] 2000 also saw the *Nine O'Clock News* moved to the later time of 22:00.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This was in response to ITN who had just moved their popular *News at Ten* programme to 23:00.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] ITN briefly returned *News at Ten* but following poor ratings when head-to-head against the BBC's *Ten O'Clock News*, the ITN bulletin was moved to 22.30, where it remained until 14 January 2008.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The retirement in 2009 of Peter Sissons and departure of Michael Buerk from the *Ten O'Clock News* led to changes in the BBC One bulletin presenting team on 20 January 2003.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* became double headed with George Alagiah and Sophie Raworth after Huw Edwards and Fiona Bruce moved to present the *Ten*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A new set design featuring a projected fictional newsroom backdrop was introduced, followed on 16 February 2004 by new programme titles to match those of BBC News 24.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News 24 and BBC World introduced a new style of presentation in December 2003, that was slightly altered on 5 July 2004 to mark 50 years of BBC Television News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The individual positions of editor of the *One* and *Six O'Clock News* were replaced by a new daytime position in November 2005.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Kevin Bakhurst became the first Controller of BBC News 24, replacing the position of editor.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Amanda Farnsworth became daytime editor while Craig Oliver was later named editor of the *Ten O'Clock News*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Bulletins received new titles and a new set design in May 2006, to allow for *Breakfast* to move into the main studio for the first time since 1997.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The new set featured Barco videowall screens with a background of the London skyline used for main bulletins and originally an image of cirrus clouds against a blue sky for *Breakfast*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This was later replaced following viewer criticism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The studio bore similarities with the ITN-produced ITV News in 2004, though ITN uses a CSO virtual studio rather than the actual screens at BBC News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News became part of a new BBC Journalism group in November 2006 as part of a restructuring of the BBC.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The then-Director of BBC News, Helen Boaden reported to the then-Deputy Director-General and head of the journalism group, Mark Byford until he was made redundant in 2010.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 18 October 2007, ED Mark Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures" (based on his project begun in March 2005), merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The various separate newsrooms for television, radio and online operations were merged into a single multimedia newsroom.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Programme making within the newsrooms was brought together to form a multimedia programme making department.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC World Service director Peter Horrocks said that the changes would achieve efficiency at a time of cost-cutting at the BBC.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In his blog, he wrote that by using the same resources across the various broadcast media meant fewer stories could be covered, or by following more stories, there would be fewer ways to broadcast them.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A new graphics and video playout system was introduced for production of television bulletins in January 2007.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This coincided with a new structure to BBC World News bulletins, editors favouring a section devoted to analysing the news stories reported on.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The first new BBC News bulletin since the *Six O'Clock News* was announced in July 2007 following a successful trial in the Midlands.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The summary, lasting 90 seconds, has been broadcast at 20:00 on weekdays since December 2007 and bears similarities with *60 Seconds* on BBC Three, but also includes headlines from the various BBC regions and a weather summary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] As part of a long-term cost cutting programme, bulletins were renamed the *BBC News at One*, *Six* and *Ten* respectively in April 2008 while BBC News 24 was renamed BBC News and moved into the same studio as the bulletins at BBC Television Centre.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC World was renamed *BBC World News* and regional news programmes were also updated with the new presentation style, designed by Lambie-Nairn.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] 2008 also saw tri-media introduced across TV, radio, and online.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The studio moves also meant that Studio N9, previously used for BBC World, was closed, and operations moved to the previous studio of BBC News 24.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Studio N9 was later refitted to match the new branding, and was used for the BBC's UK local elections and European elections coverage in early June 2009.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A strategy review of the BBC in March 2010, confirmed that having "the best journalism in the world" would form one of five key editorial policies, as part of changes subject to public consultation and BBC Trust approval.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] After a period of suspension in late 2012, Helen Boaden ceased to be the Director of BBC News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On 16 April 2013, incoming BBC Director-General Tony Hall named James Harding, a former editor of *The Times* of London newspaper as Director of News and Current Affairs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] From August 2012 to March 2013, all news operations moved from Television Centre to new facilities in the refurbished and extended Broadcasting House, in Portland Place.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The move began in October 2012, and also included the BBC World Service, which moved from Bush House following the expiry of the BBC's lease.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This new extension to the north and east, referred to as "New Broadcasting House", includes several new state-of-the-art radio and television studios centred around an 11-storey atrium.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The move began with the domestic programme *The Andrew Marr Show* on 2 September 2012, and concluded with the move of the BBC News channel and domestic news bulletins on 18 March 2013.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The newsroom houses all domestic bulletins and programmes on both television and radio, as well as the BBC World Service international radio networks and the BBC World News international television channel.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News and CBS News established an editorial and newsgathering partnership in 2017, replacing an earlier long-standing partnership between BBC News and ABC News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organisations, BBC News was ranked the fourth most trusted news organisation by Americans, behind CBS News, ABC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In January 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 450 staff reductions from the current 6,000.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] A further 70 staff reductions were announced in July 2020.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC Three began airing the news programme *The Catch Up* in February 2022.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] It is presented by Levi Jouavel, Kirsty Grant, and Callum Tulley and aims to get the channel's target audience (16 to 34-year olds) to make sense of the world around them while also highlighting optimistic stories.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Compared to its predecessor *60 Seconds*, *The Catch Up* is three times longer, running for about three minutes and not airing during weekends.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] According to its annual report as of December 2021, India has the largest number of people using BBC services in the world.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In May 2025, following the earthquake that hit Myanmar and Thailand, a television news bulletin (BBC News Myanmar) from the Burmese service using a vacated Voice of America satellite frequency began its broadcasts.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Government officials including Cyprus president Nikos Christodoulides and European lawmakers began responding to the investigation's findings in less than 24 hours, calling for reforms and launching probes.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News is responsible for the news programmes and documentary content on the BBC's general television channels, as well as the news coverage on the BBC News Channel in the UK, and 22 hours of programming for the corporation's international BBC World News channel.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Coverage for BBC Parliament is carried out on behalf of the BBC at Millbank Studios, though BBC News provides editorial and journalistic content.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News content is also output onto the BBC's digital interactive television services under the BBC Red Button brand, and until 2012, on the Ceefax teletext system.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The music on all BBC television news programmes was introduced in 1999 and composed by David Lowe.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] It was part of the re-branding which commenced in 1999 and features 'BBC Pips'.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The general theme was used on bulletins on BBC One, News 24, BBC World and local news programmes in the BBC's Nations and Regions.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Lowe was also responsible for the music on Radio One's *Newsbeat*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The theme has had several changes since 1999, the latest in March 2013.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC Verify service was launched in 2023 to fact-check news stories, followed by BBC Verify Live in 2025.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC Radio News produces bulletins for the BBC's national radio stations and provides content for local BBC radio stations via the General News Service (GNS), a BBC-internal news distribution service.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News does not produce the BBC's regional news bulletins, which are produced individually by the BBC nations and regions themselves.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC World Service broadcasts to some 150 million people in English as well as 27 languages across the globe.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC Radio News is a patron of the Radio Academy.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News Online is the BBC's news website.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Launched in November 1997, it is one of the most popular news websites, with 1.2 billion website visits in April 2021, as well as being used by 60% of the UK's internet users for news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The website contains international news coverage as well as entertainment, sport, science, and political news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Mobile apps for Android, iOS and Windows Phone systems have been provided since 2010.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Many television and radio programmes are also available to view on the BBC iPlayer and BBC Sounds services.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC News channel is also available to view 24 hours a day, while video and radio clips are also available within online news articles.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In October 2019, BBC News Online launched a mirror on the dark web anonymity network Tor in an effort to circumvent censorship.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC is required by its charter to be free from both political and commercial influence and answers only to its viewers and listeners.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] This political objectivity is sometimes questioned.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] For instance, *The Daily Telegraph* (3 August 2005) carried a letter from the KGB defector Oleg Gordievsky, referring to it as "The Red Service".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Books have been written on the subject, including anti-BBC works like *Truth Betrayed* by W J West and *The Truth Twisters* by Richard Deacon.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC has been accused of bias by Conservative MPs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC's Editorial Guidelines on Politics and Public Policy state that while "the voices and opinions of opposition parties must be routinely aired and challenged", "the government of the day will often be the primary source of news".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC is regularly accused by the government of the day of bias in favour of the opposition and, by the opposition, of bias in favour of the government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Similarly, during times of war, the BBC is often accused by the UK government, or by strong supporters of British military campaigns, of being overly sympathetic to the view of the enemy.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] An edition of *Newsnight* at the start of the Falklands War in 1982 was described as "almost treasonable" by John Page, MP, who objected to Peter Snow saying "if we believe the British".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] During the first Gulf War, critics of the BBC took to using the satirical name "Baghdad Broadcasting Corporation".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Conversely, some of those who style themselves anti-establishment in the United Kingdom or who oppose foreign wars have accused the BBC of pro-establishment bias or of refusing to give an outlet to "anti-war" voices.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Following the 2003 invasion of Iraq, a study by the Cardiff University School of Journalism of the reporting of the war found that nine out of 10 references to weapons of mass destruction during the war assumed that Iraq possessed them, and only one in 10 questioned this assumption.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] It also found that, out of the main British broadcasters covering the war, the BBC was the most likely to use the British government and military as its source.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] It was also the least likely to use independent sources, like the Red Cross, who were more critical of the war.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] When it came to reporting Iraqi casualties, the study found fewer reports on the BBC than on the other three main channels.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The report's author, Justin Lewis, wrote "Far from revealing an anti-war BBC, our findings tend to give credence to those who criticised the BBC for being too sympathetic to the government in its war coverage.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Prominent BBC appointments are constantly assessed by the British media and political establishment for signs of political bias.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The appointment of Greg Dyke as Director-General was highlighted by press sources because Dyke was a Labour Party member and former activist, as well as a friend of Tony Blair.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Mark Thompson, former Director-General of the BBC, admitted the organisation has been biased "towards the left" in the past.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] He said, "In the BBC I joined 30 years ago, there was, in much of current affairs, in terms of people's personal politics, which were quite vocal, a massive bias to the left".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] He then added, "The organization did struggle then with impartiality.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Now it is a completely different generation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Following the EU referendum in 2016, some critics suggested that the BBC was biased in favour of leaving the EU.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] For instance, in 2018, the BBC received complaints from people who took issue that the BBC was not sufficiently covering anti-Brexit marches while giving smaller-scale events hosted by former UKIP leader Nigel Farage more airtime.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] On the other hand, a poll released by YouGov showed that 45% of people who voted to leave the EU thought that the BBC was 'actively anti-Brexit' compared to 13% of the same kinds of voters who think the BBC is pro-Brexit.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 2008, the BBC Hindi was criticised by some Indian outlets for referring to the terrorists who carried out the 2008 Mumbai attacks as "gunmen".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The response to this added to prior criticism from some Indian commentators suggesting that the BBC may have an Indophobic bias.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In March 2015, the BBC was criticised for a BBC *Storyville* documentary interviewing one of the rapists in India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In spite of a ban ordered by the Indian High court, the BBC still aired the documentary "India's Daughter" outside India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News was at the centre of a political controversy following the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The government denounced the reports and accused the corporation of poor journalism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In subsequent weeks the corporation stood by the report, saying that it had a reliable source.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Following intense media speculation, David Kelly was named in the press as the source for Gilligan's story on 9 July 2003.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Kelly was found dead, by suicide, in a field close to his home early on 18 July.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] An inquiry led by Lord Hutton was announced by the British government the following day to investigate the circumstances leading to Kelly's death, concluding that "Dr.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In his report on 28 January 2004, Lord Hutton concluded that Gilligan's original accusation was "unfounded" and the BBC's editorial and management processes were "defective".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In particular, it specifically criticised the chain of management that caused the BBC to defend its story.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC Director of News, Richard Sambrook, the report said, had accepted Gilligan's word that his story was accurate in spite of his notes being incomplete.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Davies had then told the BBC Board of Governors that he was happy with the story and told the Prime Minister that a satisfactory internal inquiry had taken place.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The Board of Governors, under the chairman's, Gavyn Davies, guidance, accepted that further investigation of the Government's complaints were unnecessary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Because of the criticism in the Hutton report, Davies resigned on the day of publication.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News faced an important test, reporting on itself with the publication of the report, but by common consent (of the Board of Governors) managed this "independently, impartially and honestly".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Davies' resignation was followed by the resignation of Director General, Greg Dyke, the following day, and the resignation of Gilligan on 30 January.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] While undoubtedly a traumatic experience for the corporation, an ICM poll in April 2003 indicated that it had sustained its position as the best and most trusted provider of news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC has faced accusations of holding both anti-Israel and anti-Palestine bias.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] However two large independent studies, one conducted by Loughborough University and the other by Glasgow University's Media Group concluded that Israeli perspectives are given greater coverage.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Critics of the BBC argue that the Balen Report proves systematic bias against Israel in headline news programming.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The *Daily Mail* and *The Daily Telegraph* criticised the BBC for spending hundreds of thousands of British tax payers' pounds from preventing the report being released to the public.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] An independent panel appointed by the BBC Trust was set up in 2006 to review the impartiality of the BBC's coverage of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In some ways the picture is incomplete and, in that sense, misleading." It notes that, "the failure to convey adequately the disparity in the Israeli and Palestinian experience, [reflects] the fact that one side is in control and the other lives under occupation".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Writing in the *Financial Times*, Philip Stephens, one of the panellists, later accused the BBC's director-general, Mark Thompson, of misrepresenting the panel's conclusions.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] He further opined "My sense is that BBC news reporting has also lost a once iron-clad commitment to objectivity and a necessary respect for the democratic process.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Mark Thompson published a rebuttal in the FT the next day.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Walker argues that the independent inquiry was flawed for two reasons.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Firstly, because the time period over which it was conducted (August 2005 to January 2006) surrounded the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Ariel Sharon's stroke, which produced more positive coverage than usual.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Furthermore, he wrote, the inquiry only looked at the BBC's domestic coverage, and excluded output on the BBC World Service and BBC World.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Tom Gross, writing for the *National Review*, criticised the BBC's coverage of Hamas suicide bombers, and its invitations of Jenny Tonge and Tom Paulin as guest commentators, claiming that Paulin had "compared Jewish settlers to Nazis".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Paulin had previously stated that Israeli settlers should be "shot dead", and said he could "understand how suicide bombers feel".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC also faced criticism for not airing a Disasters Emergency Committee aid appeal for Palestinians who suffered in Gaza during 22-day war there between late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Most other major UK broadcasters did air this appeal, but rival Sky News did not.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] British journalist Julie Burchill has accused BBC of creating a "climate of fear" for British Jews over its "excessive coverage" of Israel compared to other nations.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In light of the Gaza war, the BBC suspended seven Arab journalists over allegations of expressing support for Hamas via social media.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC and ABC share video segments and reporters as needed in producing their newscasts. with the BBC showing *ABC World News Tonight with David Muir* in the UK.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] However, in July 2017, the BBC announced a new partnership with CBS News allows both organisations to share video, editorial content, and additional newsgathering resources in New York, London, Washington and around the world.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News subscribes to wire services from leading international agencies including PA Media (formerly Press Association), Reuters, and Agence France-Presse.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In April 2017, the BBC dropped Associated Press in favour of an enhanced service from AFP.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC News reporters and broadcasts are now and have in the past been banned in several countries primarily for reporting which has been unfavourable to the ruling government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] For example, correspondents were banned by the former apartheid regime of South Africa.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Zimbabwe under Mugabe for eight years as a terrorist organisation until being allowed to operate again over a year after the 2008 elections.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Burma (officially Myanmar) after their coverage and commentary on anti-government protests there in September 2007.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The ban was lifted four years later in September 2011.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Other cases have included Uzbekistan, China, and Pakistan.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] BBC Persian, the BBC's Persian language news site, was blocked from the Iranian internet in 2006.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The BBC News website was made available in China again in March 2008, but as of October 2014, was blocked again.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In June 2015, the Rwandan government placed an indefinite ban on BBC broadcasts following the airing of a controversial documentary regarding the 1994 Rwandan genocide, *Rwanda's Untold Story*, broadcast on BBC2 on 1 October 2014.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] The UK's Foreign Office recognised "the hurt caused in Rwanda by some parts of the documentary".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In February 2017, reporters from the BBC (as well as the *Daily Mail*, *The New York Times*, Politico, CNN, and others) were denied access to a United States White House briefing.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] In 2017, BBC India was banned for a period of five years from covering all national parks and sanctuaries in India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bbc-news] Following the withdrawal of CGTN's UK broadcaster licence on 4 February 2021 by Ofcom, China banned BBC News from airing in China.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/belhaven-hospital] The hospital was designed by Sydney Mitchell and George Wilson and built as an infectious diseases facility between 1903 and 1904.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/belhaven-hospital] An emergency operating theatre was added during the Second World War and the hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/belhaven-hospital] In January 2018 the hospital board announced that ward 2 would be closed for clinical use.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/belhaven-hospital] The hospital provides continuing care and GP beds for the frail and elderly.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] The hospital had its origins in a public dispensary opened by Sophia Jex-Blake at 73 Grove Street in September 1878.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] It moved to 6 Grove Street, a building large enough to provide in-patient services, as the Edinburgh Hospital and Dispensary for Women and Children in 1885.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] When Jex-Blake retired and moved away in 1899, the trustees acquired her house, Bruntsfield Lodge, and fitted it out as an 18-bed women's hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] The hospital committee was led by well-connected women active in various social reform projects such as Flora Stevenson.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] In 1910 the hospital merged with "The Hospice", a small maternity home which had been established by Elsie Inglis and the Medical Women's Club at 11 George Square some eleven years previously.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] A new ward block, designed by Arthur Forman Balfour Paul, was officially opened by Queen Mary in July 1911.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] The hospital was joined the National Health Service in 1948 and closed in 1989.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/bruntsfield-hospital] The building was then converted for residential use and is now known as Greenhill Court.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In the United Kingdom, a **listed building** is a structure of particular architectural or historical interest deserving of special protection.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Such buildings are placed on one of the four statutory lists maintained by Historic England in England, Historic Environment Scotland in Scotland, Cadw in Wales, and the Historic Environment Division of the Department for Communities in Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The classification schemes differ between England and Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland (see sections below).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The term has also been used in the Republic of Ireland, where buildings are protected under the Planning and Development Act 2000, although the statutory term in Ireland is "protected structure".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A listed building may not be demolished, extended, or altered without permission from the local planning authority, which typically consults the relevant central government agency.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In England and Wales, a national amenity society must be notified of any work to be done on a listed building which involves any element of demolition.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Exemption from secular listed building control is provided for some buildings in current use for worship, but only in cases where the relevant religious organisation operates its own equivalent permissions procedure.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Owners of listed buildings are, in some circumstances, compelled to repair and maintain them and can face criminal prosecution if they fail to do so or if they perform unauthorised alterations.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] When alterations are permitted, or when listed buildings are repaired or maintained, the owners are often required to use specific materials or techniques.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Although most sites appearing on the lists are buildings, other structures such as bridges, monuments, sculptures, war memorials, milestones and mileposts, and the Abbey Road zebra crossing made famous by the Beatles, are also listed.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Ancient, military, and uninhabited structures, such as Stonehenge, are sometimes instead classified as scheduled monuments and are protected by separate legislation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Cultural landscapes such as parks and gardens are currently "listed" on a non-statutory basis.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Although a limited number of 'ancient monuments' were given protection under the Ancient Monuments Protection Act 1882, there was reluctance to restrict the owners of occupied buildings in their actions related to their property.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The extensive damage to buildings caused by German bombing during World War II prompted efforts to list and protect buildings that were deemed to be of particular architectural merit.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Three hundred members of the Royal Institute of British Architects and the Society for the Protection of Ancient Buildings were dispatched to prepare the list under the supervision of the Inspectorate of Ancient Monuments, with funding from the Treasury.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The listings were used as a means to determine whether a particular building should be rebuilt if it was damaged by bombing, with varying degrees of success.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In Scotland, the process slightly predated the war with the Marquess of Bute (in his connections to the National Trust for Scotland) commissioning the architect Ian Lindsay in September 1936 to survey 103 towns and villages based on an Amsterdam model using three categories (A, B and C).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The basis of the current more comprehensive listing process was developed from the wartime system.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] It was enacted by a provision in the Town and Country Planning Act 1947 covering England and Wales, and the Town and Country Planning (Scotland) Act 1947 covering Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listing was first introduced into Northern Ireland under the Planning (Northern Ireland) Order 1972.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The listing process has since developed slightly differently in each part of the UK.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The process of protecting the built historic environment (i.e. getting a heritage asset legally protected) is called 'designation'.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Several different terms are used because the processes use separate legislation: buildings are 'listed'; ancient monuments are 'scheduled', wrecks are 'protected', and battlefields, gardens and parks are 'registered'.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A heritage asset is a part of the historic environment that is valued because of its historic, archaeological, architectural or artistic interest.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Only some of these are judged to be important enough to have extra legal protection through designation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Buildings that are not formally listed but still judged as being of heritage interest can still be regarded as a material consideration in the planning process.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] (right) which was itself listed in 2016.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] As a very rough guide, listed buildings are structures considered of special architectural and historical importance.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Ancient monuments are of 'national importance' containing evidential values, and can on many occasions also relate to below ground or unoccupied sites and buildings.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Buildings and structures of special historic interest come in a wide variety of forms and types, ranging from telephone boxes and road signs, to castles.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Historic England has created twenty broad categories of structures, and published selection guides for each one to aid with assessing buildings and structures.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] These include historical overviews and describe the special considerations for listing each category.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Both Historic Environment Scotland and Cadw produce guidance for owners.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In England, to have a building considered for listing or delisting, the process is to apply to the secretary of state; this can be done by submitting an application form online to Historic England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The applicant does not need to be the owner of the building to apply for it to be listed.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Full information including application form guidance notes are on the Historic England website.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Historic England assesses buildings put forward for listing or delisting and provides advice to the Secretary of State on the architectural and historic interest.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The Secretary of State, who may seek additional advice from others, then decides whether to list or delist the building.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In England, the authority for listing is granted to the Secretary of State by the Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listed buildings in danger of decay are listed on the Historic England 'Heritage at Risk' Register.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In 1980, there was public outcry at the sudden destruction of the art deco Firestone Tyre Factory (Wallis, Gilbert and Partners, 1928–29).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] It was demolished over the August bank holiday weekend by its owners Trafalgar House, who had been told that it was likely to be 'spot-listed' a few days later.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In response, the government undertook to review arrangements for listing buildings in order to protect worthy ones from such demolition.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] After the Firestone demolition, the Secretary of State for the Environment, Michael Heseltine, also initiated a complete re-survey of buildings to ensure that everything that merited preservation was on the lists.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In England, the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) works with Historic England (an agency of the DCMS), and other government departments, e.g.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Ministry of Housing, Communities, and Local Government (MHCLG) and the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (DEFRA) to deliver the government policy on the protection to historic buildings and other heritage assets.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The decision about whether or not to list a building is made by the Secretary of State, although the process is administered in England by Historic England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The listed building system in Wales formerly also operated under the Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990, as in England, until this was replaced in 2024 with Wales-specific heritage legislation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In Wales, the authority for listing is granted to the Welsh Ministers by section 76 of the Historic Environment (Wales) Act 2023, although the listing system is in practice administered by Cadw.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There have been several attempts to simplify the heritage planning process for listed buildings in England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] As of 2021, few changes had been implemented.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The review process was started in February 2000 by Alan Howarth, then minister at the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The outcome was the paper "Power of Place" in December 2000, followed by the subsequent policy document, "The Historic Environment: A Force for Our Future", published by the DCMS and the Department of the Environment, Transport and the Regions (DTLR) in December 2001.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The launch of the Government's Heritage Protection Reform (HPR) report in July 2003 by the DCMS, entitled "Protecting our historic environment: Making the system work better", asked questions about how the current designation systems could be improved.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The HPR decision report "Review of Heritage Protection: The Way Forward", a green paper published in June 2004 by the DCMS, committed the UK government and English Heritage to a process of reform, including a review of the criteria used for listing buildings.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A Review of Heritage Policy in 2006 was criticised, and the Government began a process of consultation on changes to Planning Policy Guidance 15, relating to the principles of selection for listing buildings in England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The government's White Paper "Heritage Protection for the 21st Century", published on 8 March 2007, offered a commitment to sharing the understanding of the historic environment and more openness in the process of designation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In 2008, a draft Heritage Protection Bill was subject to pre-legislative scrutiny before its passage through UK Parliament.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The legislation was abandoned despite strong cross-party support, to make room in the parliamentary legislative programme for measures to deal with the credit crunch, though it may be revived in future.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The proposal was that the existing registers of buildings, parks and gardens, archaeology and battlefields, maritime wrecks, and World Heritage Sites be merged into a single online register that will "explain what is special and why".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] English Heritage would become directly responsible for identifying historic assets in England and there would be wider consultation with the public and asset owners, and new rights of appeal.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There would have been streamlined systems for granting consent for work on historic assets.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] After several years of consultation with heritage groups, charities, local planning authorities, and English Heritage, in March 2010, the DCLG published Planning Policy Statement 5, "Planning for the Historic Environment".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] This replaced PPG15 and set out the government's national policies on the conservation of the historic environment in England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] PPS5 was supported by a Practice Guide, endorsed by the DCLG, the DCMS, and English Heritage, which explained how to apply the policies stated in PPS5.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In December 2010, the Department for Communities and Local Government announced that in England all PPSs and Planning Policy Guidance Notes would be replaced by a single document, the National Planning Policy Framework.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A consultation draft of this was published on 25 July 2011 and the final version on 27 March 2012.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] This became a material consideration in planning matters on publication.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There was formerly a non-statutory **Grade III**, which was abolished in 1970.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Additionally, Grades A, B and C were used mainly for Anglican churches in active use, loosely corresponding to Grades I, II and III.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] These grades were used mainly before 1977, although a few buildings are still listed using these grades.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In 2010, listed buildings accounted for about 2% of English building stock.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In March 2010, there were about 374,000 list entries, of which 92% were Grade II, 5.5% were Grade II* and 2.5% were Grade I.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Places of worship are an important part of the UK's architectural heritage; England alone has 14,500 listed places of worship (4,000 Grade I, 4,500 Grade II* and 6,000 Grade II) and 45% of all Grade I listed buildings are places of worship.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Some of the listed churches are no longer in use; between 1969 and 2010, some 1,795 churches were closed by the Church of England, equalling roughly 11% of the stock, with about a third listed as Grade I or Grade II.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] As of 2025, there were approximately 30,000 listed buildings in Wales, of which around 91% were Grade II, around 7% were Grade II*, and less than 2% were Grade I.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In total, listed buildings accounted for less than 1% of Welsh building stock.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The criteria for listing include architectural interest, historic interest and close historical associations with significant people or events.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Buildings not individually noteworthy may still be listed if they form part of a group that is—for example, all the buildings in a square.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Sometimes large areas comprising many buildings may not justify listing but receive the looser protection of designation as a conservation area.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The state of repair of a building is *not* generally deemed to be a relevant consideration for listing.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Although the decision to list a building may be made on the basis of the architectural or historic interest of one small part of the building, the listing protection nevertheless applies to the whole building.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listing applies not just to the exterior fabric of the building itself, but also to the interior, fixtures, fittings, and objects within the curtilage of the building even if they are not fixed.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] One example is Anmer Hall in Norfolk, which was listed in 1984 and de-listed in 1988.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In an emergency, the local planning authority can serve a temporary "**Building Preservation Notice**" (BPN), if a building is in danger of demolition or alteration in such a way that might affect its historic character.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] This remains in force for six months until the Secretary of State decides whether or not to formally list the building.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Until 2013 in England and 2016 in Wales, an application for a Certificate of Immunity from Listing (CoI) could only be made if planning permission was being sought or had been obtained.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listed building consent may be required for alterations to listed buildings, in addition to conventional planning permission.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In England and Wales, the management of listed buildings is the responsibility of local planning authorities and the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (i.e., not DCMS, which originally listed the building).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There is a general principle that listed buildings are put to 'appropriate and viable use' and recognition that this may involve the re-use and modification of the building.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] However, listed buildings cannot be modified without first obtaining Listed Building Consent through the relevant local planning authority.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In Wales, applications are made using a form obtained from the relevant local authority.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There is no provision for consent to be granted in outline.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] When a local authority is disposed to grant listed building consent, it must first notify the Welsh Parliament (*i.e.* Cadw) of the application.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] If the planning authority decides to refuse consent, it may do so without any reference to Cadw.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Carrying out unauthorised works to a listed building is a criminal offence and owners can be prosecuted.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A planning authority can also insist that all work undertaken without consent be reversed at the owner's expense.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Some energy efficiency works can be conducted without authorisation, where the works do not harm listed features.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] For example, secondary glazing is a practice where a historic, poorly insulated window can have a modern one installed behind it.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] This maintains the original facade while improving insulation, and does not usually require listed building consent.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] It is not unusual for historic sites, particularly large sites, to contain buildings with multiple, sometimes varying, designations.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] For example, Derwent Valley Mills, a World Heritage Site, contains 838 listed buildings, made up of 16 listed at Grade I, 42 at Grade II* and 780 at Grade II.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A further nine structures are scheduled monuments.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Many councils, for example, Birmingham City Council and Crawley Borough Council, maintain a list of **non-designated heritage assets** (known informally as **locally listed buildings**) as separate to the statutory list (and in addition to it).
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There is no statutory protection of a building or object on the local heritage list but the National Planning Policy Framework states that "the effect of an application on the significance of a non-designated heritage asset should be taken into account".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Many also receive a degree of protection from loss through being in a conservation area or through planning policy.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listing began later in Northern Ireland than in the rest of the UK: the first provision for listing was contained in the Planning (Northern Ireland) Order 1972; and the current legislative basis for listing is the Planning (Northern Ireland) Order 1991.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Under Article 42 of the Order, the relevant Department of the Northern Ireland Executive is required to compile lists of buildings of "special architectural or historic interest".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Following the introduction of listing, an initial survey of Northern Ireland's building stock was begun in 1974.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] By the time of the completion of this First Survey in 1994, the listing process had developed considerably, and it was therefore decided to embark upon a Second Survey, which is still ongoing, to update and cross-check the original information.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Information gathered during this survey, relating to both listed and unlisted buildings, is entered into the publicly accessible Northern Ireland Buildings Database.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A range of listing criteria, which aim to define architectural and historic interest, are used to determine whether or not to list a building.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listed building consent must be obtained from local authorities before any alteration to a listed structure.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There are about 8,500 listed buildings in Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In Scotland, listing was begun by a provision in the Town and Country Planning (Scotland) Act 1947, and the current legislative basis for listing is the Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) (Scotland) Act 1997.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] As with other matters regarding planning, conservation is a power devolved to the Scottish Parliament and the Scottish Government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The authority for listing rests with Historic Environment Scotland (formerly Historic Scotland), an executive agency of the Scottish Government, which inherited this role from the Scottish Development Department in 1991.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The listing system is administered by Historic Environment Scotland on behalf of the Scottish Ministers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Applications for consent are made on a form obtained from Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] After consulting the local planning authority, the owner, where possible, and an independent third party, Historic Environment Scotland makes a recommendation on behalf of the Scottish Ministers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] There are about 47,400 listed buildings in Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Of these, around 8 per cent (some 3,800) are Category A, 60 per cent are Category B, and 32 per cent are listed at Category C.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Although the 2008 draft legislation was abandoned, Historic England (then part of English Heritage) published a single list of all designated heritage assets within England in 2011.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The 400,000 in the listing should not be confused with the actual number of listed buildings, which will be much larger than the listing, because a listing can include more than one building that share the same listing number.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The legislative frameworks for each type of historic asset remains unchanged.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A photographic library of English listed buildings was started in 1999 as a snapshot of buildings listed at the turn of the millennium.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] This is not an up-to-date record of all listed buildings in England – the listing status and descriptions are only correct as at February 2001.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The photographs were taken between 1999 and 2008.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] It is maintained by the Historic England archive at the Images of England project website.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The National Heritage List for England contains the up-to-date list of listed buildings.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Listed buildings in danger of being lost through damage or decay in England started to be recorded by survey in 1991.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] This was extended in 1998 with the publication of Historic England's Buildings at Risk Register which surveyed Grade I and Grade II* buildings.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In 2008 this survey was renamed Heritage at Risk and extended to include all listed buildings, scheduled monuments, registered parks and gardens, registered battlefields, protected wreck sites and conservation areas.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The register is compiled by survey using information from local authorities, official and voluntary heritage groups and the general public.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] It is possible to search this list online.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In Scotland, the national dataset of listed buildings and other heritage assets can be searched online via Historic Environment Scotland, or through the map database Pastmap.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] A Buildings at Risk Register for Scotland was started in 1990 by Historic Scotland in response to similar concerns at the number of listed buildings that were vacant and in disrepair.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] RCAHMS maintained the register on behalf of Historic Scotland, and provided information on properties of architectural or historic merit throughout the country that are considered to be at risk.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Since the merger of these two bodies into one, that work is now carried out by Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Cadw publishes and maintains a searchable map database for listed buildings in Wales.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] In Wales, at risk registers of listed buildings are compiled by local planning authorities, and Cadw produced a report in 2009.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales' (RCAHMW) Emergency Buildings Recording team is responsible for surveying historic buildings threatened with destruction, substantial alteration, or serious decay.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The Northern Ireland Buildings Database contains details of all listed buildings in Northern Ireland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] The website British Listed Buildings Online has sections on England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] It can be searched either by browsing for listed buildings by country, county and parish/locality, or by keyword search or via the online map.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] Not all buildings have photographs, as it is run on a volunteer basis.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/category-a-listed] For other countries' equivalents see List of heritage registers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The **Royal Hospital for Sick Children** was a hospital in Sciennes, Edinburgh, Scotland, specialising in paediatric healthcare.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] Locally, it was commonly referred to simply as the "Sick Kids".
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The hospital provided emergency care for children from birth to their 13th birthday, including a specialist Accident and Emergency facility.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] Some in-patient specialties saw children up to their 16th birthday.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The hospital was located on Sciennes Road in the Sciennes area of Edinburgh's South Side and was managed by NHS Lothian.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] It moved in 2021 to the new Royal Hospital for Children and Young People in Little France.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The hospital, which opened at 7 Lauriston Lane in 1860, was the first dedicated children's hospital in Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] It received a royal charter in 1863, when it moved to the Meadowside House.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The conversion of the house into a hospital was carried out by the architect David Macgibbon.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] In 1890 an outbreak of typhoid forced a temporary removal to Plewlands House, Morningside, and Meadowside House was subsequently sold.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The site of the Trades Maiden Hospital (established by Mary Erskine) at Rillbank was bought in the early 1890s, and plans for a new hospital were put in hand to designs by George Washington Browne.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The Sciennes Road building, which cost £50,000, was opened by Princess Beatrice on 31 October 1895.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The First Minister, Nicola Sturgeon, visited it in November 2014.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] In February 2015 construction work began on the Royal Hospital for Children and Young People at Little France, which replaced the hospital in 2021.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] A video *Mail Porter* was commissioned in 2015 from filmmaker Sandie Jamieson, with music scored by Derek Williams to commemorate the closing of the Sciennes site.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] In December 2016 the existing site was offered for sale as a development opportunity with the expectation of significant interest.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] In September 2017 NHS Lothian decided to sell the site to the Downing Group, a Liverpool-based property developer.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The Royal Hospital for Sick Children closed on 23 March 2021.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] The Downing Group started work on the redevelopment of the site in June 2021.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] In 2011, 6-year old Jack Henderson started an initiative to raise money for the hospital that cared for his brother, by selling drawings he had created.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] He originally planned to raise £100, but quickly raised £10,000.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] A book, *Jack Draws Anything*, was published in October 2011.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] After 3 years the fundraising total exceeded £64,000 and the project was brought to an end in June 2014.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] Some of the buildings that make up the hospital at the Sciennes Road site have listed building status designated by Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] Picture tiles, manufactured by Doulton, decorated walls of wards.
[src:royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh/royal-hospital-for-sick-children-edinburgh] They depicted nursery rhymes, fairy tales and country scenes.
